				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{PtCl}}_6^{2 - }$$\end{document} anions were absorbed on the surface of HTSO due to the electrostatic force, and this was then followed by the ligand-exchange process with H2O or OH− within acidic or basic media, respectively (Eqs. 1 and 2), generating the Pt complex species28, 29; finally, the Pt complex was reduced to Pt nuclei in the heated ethylene glycol (EG) or methanol (MeOH) solvent and grows into larger Pt NPs according to the Ostwald ripening theory30. In this case, the nucleation amount determines the final size of Pt NPs; therefore, in the basic environment, the PtCl6-xOHx2-\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
